03930nam a22006255i 9780226567150DE-B159720191022022751.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||191022s2018    ilu    fo  d z      eng d  a97802265671507 a10.7208/97802265671502doi  a(DE-B1597)525047  a(OCoLC)1038796985  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  ailucUS-IL 4aPN173 7aPHI0000002bisacsh04a808.00922231 aReames, Robin, eauthor.10aSeeming and Being in Plato's Rhetorical Theory /cRobin Reames. 1aChicago : bUniversity of Chicago Press, c[2018] 4c©2018  a1 online resource (240 p.) :b1 line drawing, 1 table  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tPreface -- tINTRODUCTION. Literacy, Dramatic Form, Metaphysics -- t1. The "Cosmetics" of Sophistry -- t2. The Oral Poet and the Literate Sophist -- t3. Heraclitean Opposition and Parmenidean Contradiction -- t4. Sophistry without Measure, Dialectic without Rhetoric -- t5. The Rhetoric of Mimêsis -- t6. Imitators of Truth -- tEPILOGUE. The Past and Future of Plato's Rhetorical Theory -- tNotes -- tBibliography -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aThe widespread understanding of language in the West is that it represents the world. This view, however, has not always been commonplace. In fact, it is a theory of language conceived by Plato, culminating in The Sophist. In that dialogue Plato introduced the idea of statements as being either true or false, where the distinction between falsity and truth rests on a deeper discrepancy between appearance and reality, or seeming and being.  Robin Reames's Seeming & Being in Plato's Rhetorical Theory marks a shift in Plato scholarship. Reames argues that an appropriate understanding of rhetorical theory in Plato's dialogues illuminates how he developed the technical vocabulary needed to construct the very distinctions between seeming and being that separate true from false speech. By engaging with three key movements of twentieth- and twenty-first-century Plato scholarship-the rise and subsequent marginalization of "orality and literacy theory," Heidegger's controversial critique of Platonist metaphysics, and the influence of literary or dramatic readings of the dialogues-Reames demonstrates how the development of Plato's rhetorical theory across several of his dialogues (Gorgias, Phaedrus, Protagoras, Theaetetus, Cratylus, Republic, and Sophist) has been both neglected and misunderstood.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 22. Okt 2019) 0aPhilosophy, Ancient. 0aRhetoricxPhilosophy. 0aSophists (Greek philosophy) 4aPlato. 4abeing. 4alogos. 4amimêsis. 4aonoma. 4arhetoric. 4arhetorical theory. 4arhêma. 4aseeming. 4asophists. 7aPHILOSOPHY / General.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of Chicago Press eBook Package 2016-2018z978311063537940uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780226567150423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780226567150.jpg  a978-3-11-063537-9  University of Chicago Press eBook Package 2016-2018c2016d2018  aGBV-deGruyter-alles